If you want depth, a story, characters you can relate to and love, and more, read the book series by H.B. Gilmour and Randi Reisfeld.  They are way better than this tacky, cheesy, lame attempt at an adaption.  I wish I could of given this zero stars.

An original Disney Movie which is based on a best selling book series with the same name, starring one of the famous twins, Tia and Tamera Mowry as Alex Fielding and Camryn Barnes who was separated at birth. Taken each by their protectors, Karsh and Illeana to their safety to the next dimension, during in the peak of the war between Coventry and the Darkness, after it had taken the life of their father, Aron who had given them his every drop of powers to each of them.

Separated, each of them lead their own life, with lifestyles pretty much contrasted to each other. Camryn got adopted by David and Emily Barnes, pretty much rich folks who could afford anything for their beloved Cammy, as prove she got a car for her 16th birthday! Alex however lived her life in a lowside, living with her best friend since her mother died 2 month prior, looking for work on the side.

Karsh and Illieana stayed by them as they were growing up waiting for the time when they thought the twins are finally ready to take a hold of their destiny and they chose the day when they finally turned 21. Karsh intruded so Alex got to bump onto her long lost sister in a store. The rest of the day became a day of revelations for them. They realized in their whole life they had never parted with their past and their true home. Alex wrote stories of Coventry ever since she was a kid and active during the night and Cam drew sketches of her homeland and characters that turned out to be the Darkness and their mother. Time was running short and they needed to find a way to defeat the Darkness and meet with their long lost mother who was looking for them all of their lives, who remarried to Thantos, brother to their father.

The advert itself for the Disney Channel tempted me to watch it and the wait actually paid off! The beginning was quite baffling at first but I soon caught up with the storyline. The plot is cute in some points and nerve testing in a few but of course there's a bit of that special Disney touch of tear jerking moments. The special effects and sets are amazing and beautiful. I am in love with the Merlin-ish touch they have managed to add in and it fits lovely!

Tia and Tamera Mowry really filled up the gaps for their fans who miss them while they are away from the tv show business and I'm glad they are included in this one. I really enjoy watching this movie and I hope other people would make be willing to add this into their DVD listing as I would.

It's about (AA) twins separated at birth and adopted by different families (one a single mom, one a wealthy black couple).  Anyway, it's take on adoption was FANTASTIC in my opinion.  It's a fictional story with magic and other dimensions.  Here's what I liked about the adoption angle:

- The twins call their first mom and adoptive moms all "mom".

- One adoptive mom tells her daughter that she should NOT be worried about hurting her feelings to search for her biological mom.

- The "birthmom" word is only used once in the whole movie, to distinguish explicitly, or for anyone who doesn't "get it".

- The adoptive mom has a concept that love is infinite and you can always make more.  Just because her daughter wants to give some love to someone else, it doesn't take any away from her adoptive mom at all.

- In the end "love" is what makes the "darkness" go away - love for all kinds of family.

- At one point the first mom and adoptive parents are all together, loving up the daughter like it was normal.

And there are white brothers of black men, and white best friends of black young ladies, and rich wealthy black people with porsches, and black queens/princesses of a land, etc. etc.  Of the black / white brothers, guess which one was evil??  The WHITE one!  Although the evil force was still called the "darkness".

Many cool things about it - even if it's a bit silly and goofy on occasion.

There is a sequel, but I haven't watched it yet.

Loosely based on a book series by the same name, TWITCHES tells the story of twins Alex and Camryn, separated at birth by their protectors, who took them away to another dimension due to a war between Coventry and The Darkness. The sisters meet each other in about the same way as in SISTER, SISTER (and pretty much the same as every twins-separated-at-birth movie). Once they meet, we're forced to watch a whole series of annoying scenes where vapid, bubbly Camryn screeches about things in a high-pitched voice while her decidedly more sane sister rolls her eyes. Mainly, she's screeching about the twins' newfound magical powers, which, unlike those in better written fantasy stories, seem to be without bounds. The twins seem to just be able to touch each other's hands, recite cheesy rhyming phrases, and make just about anything happen (with terrible special effects, of course). Eventually of course, they have to stop spilling soda on people and making them wear tutus so they can find the great battle they were born to fight, against The Darkness. The Darkness is probably the worst bad guy I've ever witnessed; it's basically just a cloud of black and red smoky stuff that occasionally forms the shape of large scary hands that can grab you. Even better, once the twins face The Darkness and defeat it (with *LOVE* of course!), everyone who was previously captured by the darkness magically returns to life! Hurray! Rainbows and sunshine for everyone! In short, if you like magic and witches and sister, watch CHARMED instead. This movie is terrible.
